(652177, 36, '2016-02-02 08:10:35', '2016-02-02 13:10:35', 'Question - Does an autoclave need to be running a cycle during SQT?\n\nBackground - A client had a ''steam expert'' come in and set up their SQT program.  They cover the basics like non-condensables, dryness, and superheat.  \n\nMy concern is on the process itself.  They sample from a port in the interstitial space, near the main steam shutoff valve to the autoclave UPSTREAM of any controlling valves.  Their instructions require them to run an autoclave cycle during testing, and to sample only during the heat-up / exposure phase.  \n\nI cannot think of any advantage to sampling during a cycle at all since this is right on the main steam line.  The sample port does not know if the autoclave is in cycle, as it is always supplied with steam, and the thermo behind this testing does not make reference to static/dynamic conditions.  I do not see why this test cannot be executed without a cycle running.  \n\nAny insight is appreciated, references are doubly appreciated.  ', 'Steam Quality Testing question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'steam-quality-testing-question', '', '', '2016-02-02 08:10:35', '2016-02-02 13:10:35', '', 399865, 'http://www.sequencegxp.com/?topic=steam-quality-testing-question', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
